item.title: Video of muddy mess as tsunami waves swallow homes, villages in Japan
item.description:
Video of muddy mess as tsunami waves swallow homes, villages in Japan
Follow latest updates at http://twitter.com/rt_com and http://www.facebook.com/RTnews Japan's NHK broadcast dramatic amateur video that captured the moment that Friday's tsunami ripped through residential areas across Miyagi prefecture. Residents of the Minami-sanriku Town took to elevated ground after a tsunami warning. They watched in horror as an enormous tidal wave swept through their town, uprooting trees, houses and carrying everything in its path. Many shouted and cried as the wave continued to advance, flattening homes and swelling into a mass of water..

item.description:
Tsunami in Japan [HD] 3.11 first person FULL raw footage
This is the full raw footage filmed by some Japanese people on friday March 11th, 2011, during the tsunami which occured in northern Japan, following the 8.9 magnitude earthquake. According to the video, it was filmed in the Miyagi Prefecture (宮城) in the city of Kesennuma (気仙沼市) which has 74,000 inhabitants. More videos and pictures here : http://www.kanpai.fr/japon/tsunami-seisme-photos-videos-catastrophe-japon.html To cheer up a little, here's what nice Japan is like : http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jYoJVhxasTk Follow us on Twitter : http://www.twitter.com/kanpaifr Follow us on Facebook : http://www.facebook.com/kanpai.fr Important note : I did not filmed this footage and I cannot be held responsible for it. It was broadcasted on TV Asahi, a japanese TV channel. If it breaks any copyright, please advise me and I will remove the video. Credits to Jeffrey C. who mailed me with this HD version. item.description:
Aerial video of ravaged regions worst hit by Japan quake-tsunami
Follow latest updates at http://twitter.com/rt_com and http://www.facebook.com/RTnews Vast areas in Japan have been left unrecognisable by the devastation caused by Friday's quake and tsunami. The coastline of Miyagi prefecture was one of the worst-hit regions. Police estimated 10-thousand dead among the 2.3 million people who lived in the prefecture, the Japanese equivalent of a state. On Monday, millions of people spent a fourth night with little food, water or heating in near-freezing temperatures as they dealt with the loss of homes and loved ones.
